    "body": "### Describe the bug\r\n\r\nI try to compile multiple python modules using\r\n```\r\n\"ext_modules\": cythonize(\r\n                    module_list=[\r\n                        Extension(\r\n                            \"*\",\r\n                            [\"foo/**/*.py\"],\r\n                            define_macros=[(\"CYTHON_TRACE\", \"1\")],\r\n                        )\r\n                    ],\r\n                    exclude=[\r\n                        \"foo/**/main.py\",\r\n                        \"foo/**/__init__.py\",\r\n                        \"foo/**/server.py\",\r\n                    ],\r\n                    language_level=3,\r\n                    nthreads=multiprocessing.cpu_count(),\r\n                    compiler_directives={\r\n                        \"linetrace\": True,\r\n                        # We don't have correct enough type information to enable this.\r\n                        \"annotation_typing\": False,\r\n                    },\r\n                ),\r\n```\r\n\r\nWhen I then run the build step with `poetry install` I only ever see one `cc1` process running.\r\n\r\n### Code to reproduce the behaviour: https://github.com/rnestler/minimal-cython-nthreads-example\r\n\r\n\r\n### Expected behaviour\r\n\r\nI'd expect that there are 16 concurrent compilers running (which is what multiprocessor.cpu_count() returns on my machine)\r\n\r\n### Environment\r\n\r\nOS: Linux\r\nPython version 3.9.15\r\nCython version 3.0.0a11\r\n\r\n\r\n### Additional context\r\n\r\n_No response_",
    "closed_at": "2022-11-07T14:03:24Z",
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "I'm not completely sure (because the build system is a bit of a mystery) but I think the cythonize command only really handles the conversion of .pyx/.py files into .c files. Actually invoking the C compiler is left to distutils/setuptools and Cython doesn't really have much control of it.\r\n\r\nTherefore, I think that `nthreads` only parallelizes running Cython and not the C build. That isn't necessarily hugely helpful because the C build is usually the slower bit.",
